To solve this problem, we can use the vector triple product identity, which states that for any vectors $\mathbf{a},$ $\mathbf{b},$ and $\mathbf{c},$
\[\mathbf{a} \times (\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}) = (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c}) \mathbf{b} - (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}) \mathbf{c}.\]
We can apply this identity to each term in the given equation.
For the first term, we have
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{i} \times (\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{i}) &= (\mathbf{i} \cdot \mathbf{i}) \mathbf{v} - (\mathbf{i} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{i} \\
&= \mathbf{v} - (\mathbf{i} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{i}.
\end{align*}
Similarly, for the second term, we have
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{j} \times (\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{j}) &= (\mathbf{j} \cdot \mathbf{j}) \mathbf{v} - (\mathbf{j} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{j} \\
&= \mathbf{v} - (\mathbf{j} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{j}.
\end{align*}
And for the third term, we have
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{k} \times (\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{k}) &= (\mathbf{k} \cdot \mathbf{k}) \mathbf{v} - (\mathbf{k} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{k} \\
&= \mathbf{v} - (\mathbf{k} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{k}.
\end{align*}
Now, we can add these three terms together to get
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{i} \times (\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{i}) + \mathbf{j} \times (\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{j}) + \mathbf{k} \times (\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{k}) &= \mathbf{v} - (\mathbf{i} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{i} + \mathbf{v} - (\mathbf{j} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{j} + \mathbf{v} - (\mathbf{k} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{k} \\
&= 3 \mathbf{v} - ((\mathbf{i} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{i} + (\mathbf{j} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{j} + (\mathbf{k} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{k}).
\end{align*}
We can simplify the last term by noting that $(\mathbf{i} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{i} + (\mathbf{j} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{j} + (\mathbf{k} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{k}$ is equal to $\mathbf{v}$ itself, since the dot product of a vector with the unit vector in the same direction is the magnitude of the vector, and the cross product of a vector with the unit vector in the same direction is the zero vector.
Therefore, we have
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{i} \times (\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{i}) + \mathbf{j} \times (\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{j}) + \mathbf{k} \times (\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{k}) &= 3 \mathbf{v} - \mathbf{v} \\
&= 2 \mathbf{v}.
\end{align*}
Comparing this with the original equation, we see that $c \mathbf{v} = 2 \mathbf{v}.$ Therefore, we must have $c = \boxed{2}.$
This means that the scalar $c$ is equal to 2.
This is the final answer.

